White wine properties and quality by M. Joukamaa

In this report I am examining a dataset on white wine samples. The dataset contains measurements about several chemical and physical qualities of the samples as well as ratings given to them by wine-tasting experts.

Univariate Plots Section

As a first step of the examination, I am creating univariate plots and numerical summaries of all the different variables present in the data. In these initial examinations I am considering mostly the values from the lowest one of each variable up to the 0.75 quantile of the value range. The reason for this is that even the most cursory overview of the histograms and the value summaries below shows that the maximum values are not particularly representative of the distributions in most of the cases.

Compared to the previous chemical and physical sample properties plotted, the distribution skews more notably to the right and is especially concentrated on the lower end of the values.

The total amount of sulfur dioxide has a much wider range with the amount varying between 9 milligrams per cubic decimetre and 167 milligrams per cubic decimetre for 75 % of the samples with a median of 134 milligrams per cubic decimetre.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9871  0.9917  0.9937  0.9940  0.9961  1.0390

The density for most of the wine samples falls in a rather narrow range just very slightly below 1 (that is, the density of water). This is understandable given that wine contains ethanol, which has a density of only 0.789.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   2.720   3.090   3.180   3.188   3.280   3.820

For pH the range is also rather narrow one, varying from 2.72 to 3.28 for 75 % of the samples with a median of 3.18. Of course, since the pH scale is logarithmic, even these small differences can mean rather large and noticeable differences in the actual taste of the wine samples.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.2200  0.4100  0.4700  0.4898  0.5500  1.0800

Sulphates present in the samples range from 0.22 grams per cubic decimetre to 0.55 grams per cubic decimetre for 75 % of the samples with a median of 0.47 grams per cubic decimetre.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    8.00    9.50   10.40   10.51   11.40   14.20

The proportion of alcohol (ethanol, to be precise) in the samples ranges from 8 % to 14.2 % of the sample volume with a median of 10.4 %. The histogram for the variable shows that the distribution is somewhat right-tailed one, with a particularly large number of samples being in the 9.0 - 9.5 % alcohol volume range. On the other hand, the alcohol content distribution doesn’t have any real outliers, unlike the previous variables considered.

##    3    4    5    6    7    8    9 
##   20  163 1457 2198  880  175    5

Finally, there is the histogram and value summary for the wine quality samples as judged by at least three wine-tasting experts. While the full rating scale for quality is from 0 to 10, in the current dataset no sample gets a rating lower than 3 or higher than 9. Majority of the ratings are concentrated in the 5-7 middle value range.

Univariate Analysis

So, the dataset consists of 4898 observations of 13 different variables. Twelve of these variables are actual measurements made on the various chemical/physical qualities of the wine samples. The final variable is a rating on a 0-10 scale given to the wine sample by at least three wine experts. As the expert rating attempts to quantify the overall ‘goodness’ of a wine sample, this metric can be considered to be the response/dependent variable in relation to the chemical/ physical qualities. Also, while it is impossible for the expert ratings to affect the measured qualities in any way, the measured qualities most probably affect the expert ratings in some manner.

As the histograms above show, most of the chemical/physical qualities of the wine samples tend to have a roughly normal distribution across the different samples. However, the plots also show that pretty much all of the distributions have more or less right-skewing tails. Related to this, it is also worth noting that as the numerical summaries clearly show, the maximum values for almost all of the above distributions are markedly larger than the upper bound of 0.75 quantile, which indicates that there are outliers present in the distributions.

There are also two variables which have distributions that don’t really conform to the properties of a normal distribution. As noted before, the amount of residual sugar in the samples is heavily concentrated in the lowest levels of the value range. Another variable that doesn’t quite fit the normal distribution mold is the alcohol content of the samples which is also somewhat concentrated on the low end of the value range, though not as dramatically as the residual sugar levels. I will apply some additional attention on these two variables in the next section to make some more sense of these distributions.

The data seems tidy enough as it is, so any transformations or other operations to tidy it up don’t seem necessary. However, I did make a factor version of the expert rating variable to be used alongside the original variable in those situations and examinations where it is necessary to use a factor-scale variable.

Bivariate Plots Section

Based on the considerations lined out above, the main question of interest concerning the dataset is whether an association can be found between the chemical/physical qualities of a wine sample and the rating given to it by the wine-tasting experts. To investigate that question, I start by making boxplots of all the said qualities grouped by the expert ratings as well as calculating Pearson’s correlation coefficients for these qualities in relation to the ratings.

I am also examining if there are observeable associations between some of the other variables of the dataset as well. I am first taking a look at the relationship between the alcohol content of a wine sample and the amount of residual sugar present in it. As the sugar of the grapes tranforms into ethanol during the fermentation process of the wine, my initial assumption would be that those wine samples with a higher alcohol content would have less residual sugar present in them.

Bivariate Analysis

For most of the chemical/physical qualities of the wine samples there doesn’t seem to be any particularly noteworthy variation when they are examined across the expert ratings. The value ranges for most of the variables are rather narrow to begin with, and especially when looking at the median values, the variation doesn’t seem to exhibit discernible patterns for most of the variables. Also, most of the coefficients calculated for correlations between the quality ratings and other variables are not particularly strong.

However, a few of the chemical/physical qualities of the samples exhibit an association with the expert ratings that are clear and consistent enough to warrant further examination. In terms of the correlation coefficients, the strongest associations that the expert ratings have are with alcohol content (r = 0.44), density (r = -0.31), chlorides (r = -0.21), volatile acidity (r = -0.19), and total amount of sulfur dioxide (r = -0.17).

When looking at the boxplots of these variables by the levels of expert ratings, they mostly show similar relationships and trends as indicated by the correlation coefficients. However, it is worth noting that the boxplots for chloride and volatile acidity levels show numerous instances of outliers in the distributions of these variables. This factor calls for prudence in further analyses concerning these two variables.

With regards to the density of the samples, the scatter plot of sample density vs. alcohol content which ends the previous section shows a clear (and linear) relationship between these two variables. This is also affirmed by the strong correlation coefficient (r = -0.78) of the variables. Thus, the density of the samples can be considered to be mostly a function of their alcohol content and should be dropped from further investigations as a superfluous and possibly confounding variable.

However, given that the alcohol content of the samples affects their density in observeable amounts, the couple of outliers that have a density above that of water invite some interesting speculation. Could it be that the samples in question have also some foreign substances present in them that increase their density to a marked degree?

Finally, the plot of residual sugar vs. alcohol content presents a more complex relationship. While in general terms the samples with higher alcohol levels tend to have lower amounts of residual sugar, there are also samples with low levels of both alcohol and residual sugar. So while there are wine samples where the fermentation process has not processed all of the sugar into ethanol, there are probably also grape strains with lower levels of sugar to begin with - and thus also low levels of alcohol in the end product as well.

Multivariate Plots Section

In the previous section four variables were identified which exhibited noteworthy relationships with the quality ratings of the samples: alcohol content, total amount of sulfur dioxide, volatile acidity and chloride levels of the samples. Next, I am making several scatter plots to see if the pairwise plotting of these chemical/physical qualities grouped by the expert rating levels shows any clear trivariate relationships between these variables.

Multivariate Analysis

Most of the scatter plots I made above don’t really present any discernible patterns of trivariate relationships between the two variables plotted and the grouping made by expert ratings. While in some of the plots the best-rated wines are clearly concentrated in a certain end of one of the axes, the expert ratings tend to be all over the place in terms of the other plotted variable. The numerous outliers present in the volatile acidity and chloride distributions that were noted previously account undoubtedly for a lot of this noise. Still, the lack of discernible patterns in most of the above plots doesn’t probably return exclusively to the effect of the outliers.

However, the scatter plot of total sulfur dioxide amount versus alcohol content seems to show a clear and discernible relationship between the three different variables examined. The best-rated wines are concentrated mostly not only in the high end of the alcohol volume scale but also in the lower ratings of total sulfur dioxide amount. Thus, according to these results, in order for a wine to achieve a good expert rating it needs to have a relatively high alcohol volume, but the amount of sulfur dioxide in it should also be rather low.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The plot above shows a strong and clear relationship between the alcohol content of the wine samples and expert ratings given to them. This relationship is not entirely straightforward, though. As can be seen in the plot, there is a slight upward trend in the alcohol content of the samples toward the lower range of the ratings scale as well. But in general it can be said that wine samples with higher alcohol content tend to also get higher expert ratings.

Plot Two

Description Two

This second plot show that for the total amount of sulfur dioxide in the samples the higher ratings are associated with a downward trend for the sulfur dioxide. Even though there can be seen some slight fluctuation in the plot, the overall trend is quite clear.

Plot Three

Description Three

Combining the previous two examinations, the above plot shows how the color gradient for expert ratings moves quite clearly along both axes of the plot. Thus the best-rated wines are mostly in the high end of the alcohol content scale and low end of the sulfur dioxide amount scale with both of the variables having a roughly linear relationship with the expert ratings. When appraising the plot, it should be noted that the y-axis of the plot has been transformed into a square root scale in order to make the plot clearer and more readable.

Reflection

In this report I set out to examine a dataset of 4898 wine samples with 13 different variables measuring the chemical and physical qualities of the samples as well as rating them on their overall quality. I looked over the distributions of the individual variables and then focused more closely on how the different chemical and physical qualities were associated with quality ratings of the samples. In the end, I found a rather clear and straightforward three-way relationship between the sample ratings, their alcohol content and the total amount of sulfur dioxide in them.

It was somewhat sobering (pun intended) to see how strongly the alcohol content was correlated with the ratings given to the samples by wine-tasting experts, as even these experts seem to mostly favor strong wines over lighter ones. While some of the other objective properties of the wine samples were also associated with the expert rating levels to some degree, the negative relationship with the total amount of sulfur dioxide provided a particularly distinguishable fit when coupled with the alcohol content.

The examination of the dataset was mostly a rather straightforward job, though of course time-consuming in nature. Probably the most vexing part of the examination was figuring out which of the bivariate relationships were significant enough to warrant further investigation. Stylistical considerations for the three summary plots necessitated also several trial-and-error iterations before arriving to their final designs.

While further analyses about the relationships between the different chemical and physical properties of the samples can always be made, more fruitful work on the samples would probably benefit from additional data. For example, information about grape strains used or fermentation times and conditions could probably provide all kinds of interesting insights when combined with the current data. Another possible avenue of investigation would be to look at the prices of the different wines and how much they correlate on one hand with the expert ratings, and on the other hand with the most significant chemical and physical properties of the samples.
